Hi Magnus,

you said that signing-only email isn't really useful.

I'd like to try to change your opinion with the following example.

Imagine Mary, who is a maintainer of an open source project. She=20
announces all new releases by email, and every announcement is digitally=20
signed with her OpenPGP key.

One day, Eve successfully phishes Mary and gains full control over her=20
mailbox. Eve sends an email in Mary's name to the announce list:

"Critical RCE in 3.2.x. Emergency hotfix attached. Please deploy=20
immediately, full advisory to follow."

Note that this mail will pass all the usual checks, SPF, DKIM and DMARC=20
cleanly - because it really was sent from from Mary's account.

Transport-level checks can't catch that it was Eve who sent the message.

However, among the recipients of the announcements are people who are=20
aware that email from Mary are usually signed. They have the chance to=20
notice the "urgent" announcement is unsigned, which they will probably=20
consider suspicious. Those who notify have the chance to warn others to=20
be careful before believing in the message.

Now consider the situation Mary is in once she discovers the abuse. She=20
needs to send a follow-up: "There is no RCE in 3.2, don't install that=20
hotfix. It was a false announcement, I don't know who sent it. Someone=20
must have gotten control over my email account."

But why should anyone believe that message? Her account was just=20
demonstrably compromised. Any unsigned clarification is not convincing -=20
recipients could think that the RCE warning was legitimate, and that=20
rather the follow-up is sent by someone else.

The solution is that only Mary has access to her secret key, which Eve=20
couldn't obtain just by getting access to Mary's mail account.

Mary can send a clarification email that is signed-only, and can point=20
out three things that recipients can check:
* all her previous authentic announcements were signed
* the fake RCE mail was not
* this clarification is signed again with the same key as always.

The signature helps Mary to get out of this difficult situation.

I hope this is convincing.

Thanks,
Kai


